comments.content:
The last one looks like [Jupiter](http://web.archive.org/web/20140725062428/http:/www.myfonts.com/fonts/canadatype/jupiter-pro/) from Canada Type but with added stroke thickness (possibly a graphic bleed effect on the black background).

- Mike Yanega

"WILLIAM PRINCE..." is **[Weiss (Extra Bold)](http://web.archive.org/web/20140725062428/http:/www.findmyfont.com/index.php/fonts/font-preview?fset=Adobe&ffam=Weiss%20Std%20-%20Extra%20Bold&fid=f02ddbaaac27409faedf22f6f6198213&fsize=60&text=WILLIAM%20PRINCE%20DAKIN%20MATTHEWS&wrap=2)** by Emil Rudolf Weiss [1926]

"Yard, 2006..." looks like **[ITC Century Condensed (Bold)](http://web.archive.org/web/20140725062428/http:/www.findmyfont.com/index.php/fonts/font-preview?fset=ITC&ffam=ITC%20Century%20Condensed%20-%20Bold&fid=2c3b36378a85b6a31043ff796472a1c8&fsize=60&text=Catalog%20entry%20quotes%20from%20Art%2C%20Life%20%26%20Confussion%2F47%202006&wrap=2)**  
[PS: Sorry R. I checked again and I think /C and /& of Centennial is off.]

Just a request for the future, aq54, please separate your posts. It is hard to track multiple requests or credit multiple answers.

Also, I agree with Fivos about WILLIAM PRINCE being Weiss Extra Bold. The W fooled me, because it is different than the lighter weight.

- Mike Yanega
